tersection of two already vibrant fields: medieval material culture and medieval sensory experience. The rich potential of medieval matter (most obviously manuscripts and visual imagery, but also liturgical objects, coins, textiles, architecture, graves, etc.) to complement and even transcend purely textual sources is by now well established in medieval scholarship across the disciplines. So, too, attention to medieval sensory experiences—most prominently emotion—has transformed our understanding of medieval religious life and spirituality, violence, power, and authority, friendship, and constructions of both the self and the other. Our purpose in this volume is to draw the two approaches together, plumbing medieval material sources for traces of sensory experience - above all ephemeral and physical experiences that, unlike emotion, are rarely fully described or articulated in texts.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aMaterial culturexSocial aspects. 0aMaterial culture. 0aSocial archaeology. 0aVisual perception. 4aMaterielle Kultur. 4aMittelalter. 4aObjekt. 4aSinneserfahrung. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aSenses.  amedieval culture.  aobjects.1 aBlessing, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorland, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarver, Valerie L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffiths, Fiona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffiths, Fiona, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHahn, Cynthia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerman, Melissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNewhauser, Richard, econtrib